<h2>Understanding Alcohol Use Disorder</h2>
<p>Alcohol use disorder (AUD) affects approximately 29 million Americans. It is characterised by impaired control over drinking, continued use despite consequences, tolerance, and withdrawal. It exists on a spectrum from mild to severe — and at every point on that spectrum, effective treatment exists.</p>

<p>AUD is a chronic but treatable condition, not a moral failing or a character defect. The neuroscience of addiction is clear: heavy alcohol use changes the brain's reward circuitry, stress response systems, and prefrontal control in ways that maintain compulsive use. These changes are real, they have identified treatment targets, and they are reversible with sustained abstinence or significant reduction.</p>

<h2>The Treatment Landscape</h2>
<p>Fewer than 10% of people with AUD receive treatment in any given year. Shame, stigma, and the belief that one should be able to stop alone are major barriers. The evidence is that AUD responds to treatment — people with AUD who engage in treatment have significantly better outcomes than those who try to stop on their own.</p>

<h2>Evidence-Based Psychological Approaches</h2>

<h3>Motivational Interviewing (MI)</h3>
<p>MI is a collaborative, non-confrontational style developed specifically for ambivalence about change — the state most people with AUD inhabit. It draws out the person's own motivations for change rather than confronting or lecturing. Multiple meta-analyses show MI produces significant reductions in drinking, particularly when the person is not yet ready for abstinence-focused treatment.</p>

<h3>Cognitive Behavioral Therapy for AUD</h3>
<p>CBT for AUD addresses the triggers, coping deficits, and cognitive patterns that maintain drinking. It teaches coping skills to manage cravings, identifies high-risk situations, and addresses the beliefs about alcohol (relief from stress, social facilitation) that make it functionally attractive. CBT is typically combined with motivational approaches and medication.</p>

<h3>Relapse Prevention</h3>
<p>RP teaches people to identify warning signs of relapse, develop specific coping plans, and understand the abstinence violation effect (the "I've already ruined it so I may as well keep drinking" response) that turns lapses into full relapses. It's a structured skills approach with good long-term outcomes.</h3>

<h2>Medication-Assisted Treatment</h2>
<p>Several FDA-approved medications significantly improve AUD outcomes and are significantly underused:</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Naltrexone:</strong> Reduces alcohol craving and blunts the reward response to alcohol. Strong evidence for reducing heavy drinking days. Available as daily pill or monthly injection (Vivitrol).</li>
  <li><strong>Acamprosate:</strong> Reduces the negative emotional states (anxiety, dysphoria) during abstinence that drive relapse. Most effective when abstinence is already established.</li>
  <li><strong>Disulfiram:</strong> Produces unpleasant reactions when alcohol is consumed. Effective for people who want a strong deterrent and are motivated for abstinence.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Safe Withdrawal: An Important Note</h2>
<p>Alcohol withdrawal is uniquely dangerous — unlike opioid or stimulant withdrawal, it can be life-threatening in severe dependence. If you drink heavily and regularly, do not stop suddenly without medical guidance. Medically supervised withdrawal is available and safe. This is a medical consideration, not a character comment.</p>

<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

<p><strong>Do I need to want to stop completely to get therapy?</strong><br/>
No. Motivational interviewing and harm reduction approaches work with wherever you are, including with goals of reducing drinking rather than abstaining. As ambivalence resolves and treatment progresses, goals often shift.</p>

<p><strong>Is online therapy appropriate for serious alcohol problems?</strong><br/>
For mild to moderate AUD without serious withdrawal risk, online therapy is effective. For severe dependence with physical withdrawal risk, starting with medical detox and in-person treatment is safer before transitioning to online maintenance therapy.</p>

